title: XC323488 Alder Flycatcher (Empidonax alnorum)
secondary_labels: ['Geothlypis trichas_Common Yellowthroat', 'Zonotrichia albicollis_White-throated Sparrow', "Catharus ustulatus_Swainson's Thrush", 'Empidonax traillii_Willow Flycatcher']
description:
Singing from trees adjacent to ponds. There is an interesting double-vocalization at 1:20.5, where either the bird stutters or a second individual sings nearby. Perhaps it is a Willow Flycatcher? Also, Willow Flycatcher at 0:05?

## Conditions

 Clear sky, about 60°F,  warming from an overnight freeze.

## Equipment

Recorded on a Sennheiser MKE 400 microphone with a wind baffle into a Panasonic GH2 camera at 192 kbps.

## Modifications

 Trimmed stretches without songs from front  and back. Amplified to peak at –3.0 dB.
background: Common Yellowthroat (Geothlypis trichas); White-throated Sparrow (Zonotrichia albicollis); Swainson's Thrush (Catharus ustulatus); Willow Flycatcher (Empidonax traillii)

title: XC141320 American Bittern (Botaurus lentiginosus)
secondary_labels: ['Geothlypis trichas_Common Yellowthroat', 'Melospiza melodia_Song Sparrow', "Catharus ustulatus_Swainson's Thrush", 'Empidonax alnorum_Alder Flycatcher']
description:
- two songs by same adult male.
- extraneous sounds edited by silencing rather than cutting out to preserve time interval between songs.
- bird singing from near east edge of Newlands Marsh, approximately 15 meters north of Upper Fraser Road.
- habitat is fresh water marsh surrounded by mixed deciduous/coniferous forest and grass pastures.
- UTM coordinates of bird from Google Earth: Zone 10U 551928.72 E, 5995802.24 N (WGS84)
- the bittern takes four or five gulps of air to fill his lungs before singing and you can here the bill snapping shut after every intake of air before the booming begins.
- recording device: H2 Zoom; microphone: Sennheiser ME-66; recording is mono even though the H2 labeled the file as stereo.
- sound editing done in Audacity.
- recording available in WAV format upon email request.
background: Common Yellowthroat (Geothlypis trichas); Song Sparrow (Melospiza melodia); Swainson's Thrush (Catharus ustulatus); Alder Flycatcher (Empidonax alnorum)

title: XC378969 American Bittern (Botaurus lentiginosus)
secondary_labels: ['Cistothorus palustris_Marsh Wren', 'Hirundo rustica_Barn Swallow', 'Bombycilla cedrorum_Cedar Waxwing']
description: We had heard another individual singing across the beach marshland less than 30 minutes previously, so this bird could be a female, its mate. Flight call as it flushed and flew away from me. Pretty startling, almost stepping on a completely camouflaged Bittern... Anyway, weather cool (~50 degrees F), no wind, overcast. Habitat: beach marshland, probably all freshwater, thick pond vegetation (short reedy grass and whatnot), a few short (~1 m) scrubby deciduous trees. Bird was only 2m away from me when we surprised each other, and I pounded "Record". Short earsplitting click from that was removed at beginning, though a small remnant remains in its first call. Very low high pass filter applied to reduce noise, as recording was amplified (its calls were very quiet, and of course, it was not facing me as it flew away).
background: Marsh Wren (Cistothorus palustris); Barn Swallow (Hirundo rustica); Cedar Waxwing (Bombycilla cedrorum)
author: Rachel Hudson

title: XC396690 American Wigeon (Mareca americana)
description:
This is a recording of group of about 120 American Wigeons that spend most nights in this area during winter.  The group is generally silent except for calls from 1 or 2 birds, except when small groups of other Wigeons arrive.  This recording includes calls during the separate arrivals of 4 groups of smaller numbers of Wigeons.  There are calls from some of the new arrivals, as they swim closer, and a chorus of calls from the established larger group. 

The recording is made at 9:30 p.m., more than 5 hours after 4:22 p.m. sunset.  The Wigeons are a resting in the ocean 1 to 5 meters from a sandy beach.  There are about a dozen Mallards resting on the beach.  There is a Great Blue Heron resting on a nearby rock but is not heard in this recording.
background: Mallard (Anas platyrhynchos)
author: Barry Edmonston

title: XC171994 American Woodcock (Scolopax minor)
description:
Second of three recordings from 26 March 2014 between 8:05-8:20pm, from the north end of the Godown Road Park (Dog Park) on the east side of the OSU Airport area off Godown Rd, Columbus, OH.  There were multiple birds present and calling/displaying, but the recordings focused on one individual "peent"calling from the ground, then (in this recording) flying off giving twittering areal display calls before (not in this recording) returning to the same site.  Habitat: Mixed brush, sparse trees and heavily impacted grassland mix.
Recording made using a Sennheiser ME67 shotgun mic and a Sony Hi-MD recorder, model MZ-RH910 and cleaned up using Audacity: High Pass filter (2k, 5q, 12db) and noise removal.  
WAV version at https://soundcloud.com/paul-j-hurtado/american-woodcock-1-3.  
eBird Checklist: http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S17613891
background: Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
author: Paul J. Hurtado

title: XC217766 American Woodcock (Scolopax minor)
location: Mount Vernon (near  Alexandria), Fairfax County, Virginia
description:
This recording was extracted from a video recorded on a Canon 7D mark II DSLR using the on-camera mic.  An FFT filter was used to affect an exponential roll-off in volume below 3 kHz to remove the sound of nearby George Washington Memorial Highway.   Adobe Audition's "adaptive noise removal" filter was then applied to get rid of background hiss.    One brief section of about 2 seconds in the middle of the video was removed in which a person in my group spoke.  The AMWO was in flight and distant at that point; no significant audio was lost.  

The recording was made while standing on the "dogleg" portion of the Haul Road trail at Dyke Marsh.  There were at least three male American Woodcocks in the area, and the one recorded here was within four meters while on the ground.  It was doing the standard AMWO breeding display which starts with a number of nasal "peent" calls followed (at 0:20) by a rapid vertical flight in which the tail feathers make a sound reminiscence of that made by Mourning Doves.   The bird reached an altitude of maybe 20 meters, then flew around in a wide circle, reaching its farthest point from me at about 0:42.   As the bird returned to its starting point above me at about 1:00, it began making the characteristic rapid chirp calls as it descended.  When it reaches the ground at 1:18, the bird goes totally silent.  The "peents" would start up a few seconds later and this cycle was repeated numerous times over the course of about 15 minutes.
background: Mallard (Anas platyrhynchos); Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
author: Mouser Williams

title: XC309337 American Woodcock (Scolopax minor)
location: Newton Hills SP, Lincoln Co., South Dakota
description: Recording of several American Woodcock, one at close range, during mating display at Newton Hills State Park Horse Camp. Habitat was a large clearing with low sumac and grass and interspersed cedar surrounded in much taller, thicker deciduous forest with nearby creek. Recording began after dark at 8:26 PM. Primary bird was on ground 15-20 feet away, observed in this spot through the sumac before dark, located via its "peent" call. Bird would jerk head back with bill open wide during "peent" call. After several "peent" calls, birds would fly high into air making whistling sound with wings on ascent, chirping sound upon descent, returning to or very near location from which they took flight. Several silhouettes observed in air.
background: Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
author: Joe C

title: XC127999 American Tree Sparrow (Spizelloides arborea)
secondary_labels: ['Cardinalis cardinalis_Northern Cardinal', 'Aix sponsa_Wood Duck', 'Turdus migratorius_American Robin', 'Poecile atricapillus_Black-capped Chickadee', 'Melospiza melodia_Song Sparrow', 'Anas platyrhynchos_Mallard', 'Branta canadensis_Canada Goose']
description:
Songs and calls from a wintering flock of 20-30 in a patch of scrub in oak savanna. This recording is comprised of several segments with slight breaks between them.  Most of the time, the birds were calling, singing, and chasing eachother around the bushes.  Occasionally small groups would make forays out into the grasses to forage, and then return.

At approximately 8:36, a Northern Shrike appears. There's an alarm call from one of the sparrows and they all stop singing and dive into the thickest part of the scrub.  Chickadees start scolding. There is some thrashing of wings as the shrike chases the birds (unsuccessfully) through the bushes, and all of the birds scatter.

Recorded from about 10m. Windy, cold, and overcast.  Filtered low frequencies slightly for wind, traffic, and airplane noise. Recorded with Olympus LS-10S and homemade parabolic reflector.
background: Northern Cardinal (Cardinalis cardinalis); Wood Duck (Aix sponsa); American Robin (Turdus migratorius); Black-capped Chickadee (Poecile atricapillus); Song Sparrow (Melospiza melodia); Mallard (Anas platyrhynchos); Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
author: Jonathon Jongsma

title: XC271037 Barn Swallow (Hirundo rustica)
description: The recordings begins with three calls from a passing Chough. The Chough was cruising overhead along the line of a small road. I was out of sight and screened by a barn. I think that the Chough called because it spotted me. In turn, the Swallow (an adult) joined in the commotion. Swallow alarm calls begin at 0:07. Two young Swallows were perched farther away so I assume that the adult was training them to associate the alarm call with humans. Perhaps the Swallow's nest was inside the barn (I did not look inside)  and I was too close for comfort.
author: Anthony McGeehan

title: XC361739 Barn Swallow (Hirundo rustica)
type: call, female, flight call, male, song
description: Una pareja de golondrinas ya en el período de incubación. Los sonidos que aquí aparecen son los relevos en la incubación entre los miembros de la pareja, las visitas del macho a la hembra en el nido y los intentos de expulsión de otro macho soltero que entra en la zona de nidificación. Estas aves crían en la lámpara del salón de una amiga y ya es el segundo año que se reproducen allí.
author: José Carlos Sires

title: XC428701 Barn Swallow (Hirundo rustica)
description: The clip is edited from several minutes of sounds made by two young Swallows that were sitting on a cottage roof. At least one parent was 'keeping an eye' on them and (probably) occasionally arriving to feed them.  I did not see any of the activity as I left the recorder and then played back the result. The opening ten seconds contain a burst of calls that accompanied the youngsters flying off [0:02]. This was when I left the recorder on the cottage roof, thereby disturbing them. At some point, a Wren landed on the roof and it must have perched right beside the recorder because its song is loud and clear at 0:10. After that, the Wren changes perch and the subsequent song-bursts are not so close. From 0:30, the young Swallows are resting on the roof and making typical twitters - the sound of offspring hoping to receive food from an incoming parent. It seems that, at around forty seconds, an adult flies in and may have delivered food - the calls become more intense at 0:45. Irrespective of whether the young were fed or not, they fly off at the end of the recording.
author: Anthony McGeehan

title: XC265043 Belted Kingfisher (Megaceryle alcyon)
description:
This 6+ minute recording documents various sounds of two Belted Kingfishers. One was an adult female. The other was a juvenile female. I got the sense that the adult was forcing its offspring to leave home. This recording is poorly narrated thus many of the vocalizations are not identified to the individual. But on the upside, several are.

The first 10 seconds are several highlights of the recording mostly various juvenile vocalizations. But one adult noise as well.  

0:00 Begging of juvie while being chased by adult.

0:03 Expression of contempt followed by a rattle both juvie (not supremely confident that the rattle was juvie)

0:05 Two juvenile rattles.

0:08 Adult rattle.

0:30 The juvenile performed a display flight to meet and greet a 3rd BEKI. It was a juvenile and I suspect it was a sibling.

4:56 An interesting vocalization that I have a vague recollection that the juvie made. But I’m not certain.

More details of the context of this recording may be found here: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S24410024>

This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with built-in microphone and Røde Rec application. This recording is largely an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of this bird's utterances. However, a 32 second period was removed starting at 1:56 due to a lull in the action. I also removed a 45 second period starting at 5:18 due to another lull. This recording is part of a longer 11 minute recording but due to a helicopter overflight and a brief spat between two nearby kayaker, I decided to leave it out.
background: Barn Swallow (Hirundo rustica); American Goldfinch (Spinus tristis)
author: Elias Aristides Elias

title: XC394310 Black-capped Chickadee (Poecile atricapillus)
description:
I recorded a flock of at least 6 chickadees feeding from a handheld container of peanuts and black oil sunflower seeds. The recording includes 'tseet' contact calls, 'dee-dee' calls and many gargle calls. In one case I saw one of the chickadees make a submissive posture after another chickadee made a gargle call.  The weather conditions were sunny and the temperature was around -1C with a slight breeze.

The recording also includes wing noises, the sound of a seed shell being cracked open, and the rattling of seeds in the container.

The recording was made using a Sennheiser ME-66 and a Tascam DR-05.
background: Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
author: Dan Minor

title: XC127624 Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
description:
Two pairs of early-returning geese on the ice of a still-frozen lake in an urban park.  The closest pair was approximately 10m away, the other pair about 30m.  One member of the nearby pair (presumably the female) was mostly silent and was sitting down on the ice for most of the recording.  The other goose (presumably the male) was doing most of the vocalizing.  Periodically he would give a grating crescendo call with a loud finish (e.g. heard clearly at 3:04.5, but present throughout the recording).  While doing this call, he would throw his head back, pointed up to the sky.  Immediately after these calls, he generally would nip at the back or neck of the other member of the pair.

Calls from a member of the other pair (presumably the male) in the background, slowly getting closer. One member of each pair had been observed fighting eachother several minutes before.

Airplane interlude about halfway through the recording. Light filtering below 400Hz.
author: Jonathon Jongsma

title: XC165398 Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
description:
A large flock of Canada Geese taking off. I believe most of the birds in this flock were parvipes ("Lesser") Canada Geese, but there were also larger (subspecies moffitti?) Canada Geese and a few Cackling Geese (several of the subspecies hutchinsii and possibly one of the subspecies minima) in the general vicinity. 

In the old days this would have been an "obvious" or "easy" flock of "Canada Geese." Now we're dealing with perhaps two species and probably two or three subspecies in the recording. Again, I believe most of the birds audible here are parvipes ("Lesser") Canada Geese.
author: Ted Floyd

title: XC307648 Canada Goose (Branta canadensis)
description:
Natural sound from birds flying over, approximately 30m from recordist.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
No edits.

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
background: Blue Jay (Cyanocitta cristata); American Crow (Corvus brachyrhynchos)
author: J.R. Rigby

title: XC179676 Canada Warbler (Cardellina canadensis)
secondary_labels: ['Geothlypis philadelphia_Mourning Warbler', 'Melospiza melodia_Song Sparrow', 'Molothrus ater_Brown-headed Cowbird', 'Turdus migratorius_American Robin', "Catharus ustulatus_Swainson's Thrush"]
location: OSU's Waterman Farm wood lot, Columbus, Franklin County, Ohio
description:
Recorded along the southeast margin of the wood lot on the Ohio State University experimental farm (Waterman Farm; limited access) located in urban Columbus, OH adjacent to the OSU campus (see map). The Canada Warbler was first seen and heard along a stream inside the wood lot, then moved to the edge of the wood lot while I ran back to my car to get recording equipment. There, it was mostly in honey suckle bushes or adjacent lower branches of trees along the edge of the wood lot.  I was pleasantly surprised to have a Mourning Warbler do the audio-equivalent of "photo bombing" my Canada Warbler recording!  All of this session's Mourning Warbler recordings: at the end of XC179676 and throughout XC179679 (XC179681 cropped from XC179679). All of this session's Canada Warbler recordings: XC179676, XC179679 (XC179681 cropped from XC179679), and XC179691. Audacity software was used for post-processing of recordings (signal:noise reduction via high pass filter, then amplification).  Eastern Chipmunk also audible in the background. 

eBird Checklist: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S18532024>
background: Mourning Warbler (Geothlypis philadelphia); Song Sparrow (Melospiza melodia); Brown-headed Cowbird (Molothrus ater); American Robin (Turdus migratorius); Swainson's Thrush (Catharus ustulatus)
author: Paul J. Hurtado

title: XC278703 Caspian Tern (Hydroprogne caspia)
description:
This 12 second recording documents 5 vocalizations of a juvenile, unknown sex Caspian Tern as it flew over an urban city. I first heard what I presume is the same bird 6 hours before. Upon awaking, I heard the same vocalizations and I wondered if it was the same individual. It made 10+ passes within earshot between 04:50-05:20. I assume that it is a juvenile that has been separated from its parent.

More details of the context of this recording may be found here: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S24978579>

This recording was made with an iPhone 4s with a Sennheiser mic and Røde Rec application. This is an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of this bird's utterances.
author: Elias Aristides Elias

title: XC496291 Caspian Tern (Hydroprogne caspia)
secondary_labels: ['Larus occidentalis_Western Gull', 'Regulus calendula_Ruby-crowned Kinglet', 'Megaceryle alcyon_Belted Kingfisher', 'Corvus brachyrhynchos_American Crow', 'Melozone crissalis_California Towhee', 'Thalasseus elegans_Elegant Tern']
location: Morro Bay State Park Campground (near  Morro Bay), San Luis Obispo County, California
description:
The main calls are of Caspian Terns. 
——-Elegant Tern, 3 calls at 7:03.00 and the one at 7:40.50 (overlaps with the Caspian Tern call).
———-I could not find an example to match this laughing call just after a kee-kareer and kree-er call, that seems to come from the Caspian Tern: 7:43.00 .
---------The recording get interesting after a tern dives into the water at 6:51.00 , then the ruckus starts!
———Caspian Tern whistle throughout (seem to undulate in pitch like a sin wave). Kee-kareer call at 7:14.00 . Kree-er call at 4:37.3 .

title: XC233760 Chukar Partridge (Alectoris chukar)
location: Santa Fe National Forest (near  Los Alamos), Los Alamos County, New Mexico
description:
This recording was extracted from a video taken with a Canon 7D Mk II DSLR ([see video here](https://www.flickr.com/photos/mouser-nerdbot/16970149686/)) using the internal microphone.   The sound has been processed with Adobe Audition, with the adaptive noise filter applied.

The Chukar was standing on top of a small boulder on one foot, calling every 10 seconds or so, at a distance of about 10 meters.  I was illegally parked in the middle of a building's driveway and someone drove up behind me, so I had to stop recording as soon as the first call sequence was complete.
author: Mouser Williams

Modifications to the file: cropped and amplified by 10 dB.

In a distance there are fields, homes and roads to N and NE-E.

title: XC209766 Northern Raven (Corvus corax)
location: Hot Slough, Denali National Preserve, Alaska
type: bill snapping, call, water droplet call
description:
Habitat:  Microphone was within 10 - 20 meters of several ephemoral, wooded ponds.  Within a larger scale, the site was situated within a system of wetlands and low, rocky eskers.

Bandpass from 100 - 8000 Hz, amplify +15 dBu.

Bill snapping behavior begins around 01:34, associated with "water-droplet" calls.
author: Davyd Betchkal

title: XC209767 Northern Raven (Corvus corax)
location: Hot Slough, Denali National Preserve, Alaska
type: bill snapping, call, water droplet call
description:
Habitat:  Microphone was within 10 - 20 meters of several ephemoral, wooded ponds.  Within a larger scale, the site was situated within a system of wetlands and low, rocky eskers.

Bandpass from 300 - 8000 Hz, amplify +15 dBu.

A large variety of calls in short succession.  Cut begins with ringing calls, and around 0:43 bill snapping and "water-droplet" calls occur.  See also XC209766, which occurs a few minutes earlier.
author: Davyd Betchkal

title: XC253133 Northern Raven (Corvus corax)
description: These raucous squawks were produced by members of a nine-strong troupe (I believe two family parties were involved) that settled on the roof of a farmer's home on a Sunday morning at 0640hrs. The racket was deafening and the clip was recorded roughly ten minutes after the birds arrived. I made the recording from an adjoining cottage: so you can imagine the volume for the people in the house upon whose roof the birds were sitting. The farmer had buried a dead sheep nearby the day before and the Ravens had smelled the rotten corpse. However, it was too deep for them to disinter. The noise made by the horde caused some calling among other birds in the farmer's garden: such as juvenile Blackbirds [examples at 0:03 and 0:04], Goldfinches [examples at 0:27, 0:44 and 1:06] and a Wren [example at 0:18]. Skylark song can be heard as a backdrop from 0:06 onwards and is best from 1:15 to the end. A Corncrake calls from time to time. Although faint, the Corncrake can be detected after 0:59 for about five seconds. The gull cry at 0:52 (for the next three seconds) are from a Herring Gull.
author: Anthony McGeehan

title: XC195844 Dark-eyed Junco (Junco hyemalis)
secondary_labels: ['Melospiza melodia_Song Sparrow', "Selasphorus sasin_Allen's Hummingbird", 'Sturnus vulgaris_European Starling', 'Zonotrichia leucophrys_White-crowned Sparrow', 'Anas platyrhynchos_Mallard']
location: Palace of Fine Arts (near  San Francisco), San Francisco County, California
description:
Three dependent juvenile plumaged Dark-eyed Junco (Oregon) were in area and were being fed by an adult Dark-eyed Junco (Oregon). If I recall they had nearly full-grown tails and were perhaps a week out of the nest. This recording was made at the Palace of Fine Arts, San Francisco, California (WGS84 37.802340, -122.448028). These birds were flitting around on the ground at my feet and were being fed by an adult. Two juvenile call types were recorded in this 134 second long recording: first was a buzzy begging note (quite variable) sometime given singly, other times repeated and when very excited (such as when adult approached with food) it was given rapidly. More rarely a second call was given—a brief chip—likely an analogue to the adult Chack note.  The adult Chack call was described in the BNA account as: Chack, also interpretable as tik, stip (Fig. 2F): wide-frequency, short-duration single syllable, often uttered near ground predator (Hostetter 1961); general alarm call during winter (Whitney 1968).

This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with the built-in microphone and the Røde Rec application. This recording has not been modified in any manner. This recording has some city type noises in the background.

Dark-eyed Junco (Oregon): 

begging: begins at 0:00  with an intense volley of begging is at 1:29
chipping: begins at 1:10 and at times blends into a begging note.

Song Sparrow (song): 0:00, 0:15, 0:31, 0:39

Allen’s Hummingbird: 0:15

European Starling: 0:53, 0:58, 0:59

White-crowned Sparrow (song): 1:04, 1:17

Mallard 1:36
background: Song Sparrow (Melospiza melodia); Allen's Hummingbird (Selasphorus sasin); Common Starling (Sturnus vulgaris); White-crowned Sparrow (Zonotrichia leucophrys); Mallard (Anas platyrhynchos)
author: Elias Aristides Elias

title: XC171698 Eastern Bluebird (Sialia sialis)
secondary_labels: ['Poecile atricapillus_Black-capped Chickadee', 'Turdus migratorius_American Robin', 'Melanerpes carolinus_Red-bellied Woodpecker', 'Branta canadensis_Canada Goose', 'Cardinalis cardinalis_Northern Cardinal']
description:
One of the birds from XC171662.  Several segments from the same recording session (breaks at 2:31, 3:21, 8:26).  The bird moved between perches in open oak savanna. Segments correspond to different perches. Around 3:46, a second bird flies into the tree and there is audible wing noise as they chase eachother around the tree. After the intruder is chased off, the song becomes louder and more agitated, and you can hear the second bird countersinging for a little while.

Recorded with Sennheiser ME66 and Olympus LS-10S. Temperature fairly warm but a bit overcast, still significant snow cover on the ground. Filtered low frequencies for traffic hum.
background: Black-capped Chickadee (Poecile atricapillus); American Robin (Turdus migratorius); Red-bellied Woodpecker (Melanerpes carolinus); Canada Goose (Branta canadensis); Northern Cardinal (Cardinalis cardinalis)

I added silence at the beginning and end of this recording.
This is a suburban area with an adjacent open hillside containing sagebrush. A line of about 15 mature spruce trees exixts here. This recording documents two EUCDs. One is being chased by the other. They went up and down the line of trees making this racket for quite a while. It may be a breeding behavior. You can hear their wings flapping as well.

description: Calls match Type 1 (=brooksi) spectrograms shown in Sewall et al. 2004. A few individuals calling from the top of a ponderosa pine. Amplification, low and high-pass filters used in Audacity.

title: XC268724 Golden Eagle (Aquila chrysaetos)
description:
Possible voice of this species.  I am familiar with the voice of this
species through various videos and this sounded very similar
to them.  The resultant recording was not so clear as I expected,
possibly due to the great distance from the observing location
and background cicada sounds.  The voice has a descending tone
from 3 to 2 kKz (at 0.5s), but the duration seems to be a bit short.
A young bird was witnessed to fly over this location
15 min before and I pointed the microphone to the direction
where the bird was observed.  This place is over the cliff and
other birds were only rarely heard.  I provide this recording
for consideration.  Band-pass filtering has been applied.
author: Anon Torimi

title: XC307888 Golden Eagle (Aquila chrysaetos)

author: Stein Ø. Nilsen

title: XC326800 Golden Eagle (Aquila chrysaetos)
description:
Suspected ID.  The voice was heard when we were in the fog.
We couldn't recognize the bird after the clearance of the fog.
The voice was heard from the direction where there is
a frequently used perching site (it is not directly seen from
the place of observation) according to a local observer.
The voice is different from typical adult calls, and it may
have been from a juvenile bird.  The voice is less structured,
but has some (preceding before the main note) structure
characteristic to this species at least in two notes at 8.0s and 8.9s.
A mimic by an Eurasian jay cannot be completely excluded
but I could not hear jay calls in the corresponding distance.
background: Japanese Bush Warbler (Horornis diphone)
author: Anon Torimi

title: XC385227 Golden Eagle (Aquila chrysaetos)
description:
Although this is a voice from an individual in the zoo, I provide this recording
for the reference and research in the absence of a freely available
secure recording of Aquila chrysaetos japonica (there are several
videos in YouTube).  The number of this subspecies is estimated
to be 500 (according to the page of Society for Research of Golden Eagle Japan)
and there are only 150-200 pairs.  The successful breeding rate is
very low (10-20% for well-studied pairs) and we probably have little
chance to hear the voice in the wild (considering that the birds are
most vocal in the presence of begging juveniles).
Although I have uploaded some suspected vocalizations of this
species, I provide this since I consider this recording represents the most typical voice
of this (sub)species.
The recording was made when the zoo was closed and I noticed
the voice at the entrance.  It took some time to prepare the recorder
and I only managed to take two phrases.  Although the bird was
not directly seen, the ID is secure.  It was likely that the bird begged.
(It is said that recording of this species is difficult even in zoos).

(Later comment):
I found that recently recorded calls are available on the
website:
http://www.bird-research.jp/1_shiryo/nakigoe.html
See at イヌワシ
Note that the recordings in the above page do not belong
to Creative Commons licenses.
author: Anon Torimi

title: XC135970 Great Egret (Ardea alba)
description:
gaggle of begging calls at a rookery of 100-plus nests on and island in the middle of a suburban lagoon.  Interspersed are the calls of squabbling adults.  The rookery is host to Double-crested Cormorant, Anhinga, Snowy Egret and Common Gallinule as breeders.  Others regularly on the island in surrounding trees are Black-crowned Night-Heron, Wood Stork and both Black and Turkey Vulture.

The habitat on the rookery consists of scrubby trees on which nests of sticks are constructed, and higher grasses.  Most of the behavior centered around the nestlings begging for food.  Most of the nestlings are still in the down stage, although feathers are appearing.
background: American Crow (Corvus brachyrhynchos)
author: Russ Wigh

title: XC254805 Greater Roadrunner (Geococcyx californianus)

title: XC253773 Green Heron (Butorides virescens)
secondary_labels: ["Catharus ustulatus_Swainson's Thrush", 'Icteria virens_Yellow-breasted Chat', 'Poecile atricapillus_Black-capped Chickadee']
description:
This 20-second long recording documents 2 flight displays of an adult Green Heron. This heron did an aerial display within the canopy of an Red Alder. It only made a mechanical noise with its wings. This heron had just flown into the tree from the river bed. It landed and perched for a few seconds. It then flew with the body held at a 45˚ angle and a hunched back. The wings were not lifted much above horizontal but were deeply flapped under the body. The wings were quite flared. This noise was created in the downflap. This bird flapped 10 times. This bird landed perhaps 5 meters above where it took off and disappeared from view and was not seen again. At 0:19 it made a second display also with 10 flaps. The sound source was within 15 meters of the microphone. This cut is an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of this bird’s display.

This is what the Birds of North America account has to say: "Flap Flight Display is highest intensity of flight displays, where male lurches through air with exaggerated flapping producing whom-whoom-whoom sound, neck crooked, legs dangling, skow ing, crest, neck, and scapular feathers erect, sometimes giving roo-roo calls before landing."

Davis, Jr., W. E. and J. A. Kushlan. 1994. Green Heron (Butorides virescens), The Birds of North America Online (A. Poole, Ed.). Ithaca: Cornell Lab of Ornithology; Retrieved from the Birds of North America Online: http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/129

Additional details regarding context may be found at: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S23971407>

This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with on-board microphone and Røde Rec application.
background: Swainson's Thrush (Catharus ustulatus); Yellow-breasted Chat (Icteria virens); Black-capped Chickadee (Poecile atricapillus)
author: Elias Aristides Elias

title: XC306356 Horned Lark (Eremophila alpestris)
description:
Bird was foraging in an agricultural field approximately 20-30 meters from the gravel road.

#Habitat#
Agricultural fields in the Mississippi River alluvial valley. Open fields of primarily soybeans surrounded by large ditches. Open fallow grassland of ~10-20ac near the north end of the road where Short-eared Owls regularly winter.

#Editing#
No editing other than cropping. 

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
author: J.R. Rigby

title: XC441749 House Sparrow (Passer domesticus)
description: The clip records a flush of House Sparrows brought about by a false alarm. This, of course, is a regular occurrence among all birds that face the risk of predation constantly. The false alarm was caused by the sudden appearance of a group of wild Rock Doves that flew over a feeding area used by House Sparrows, Starlings and, indeed, the Rock Doves themselves. Hence their arrival in itself caused the smaller birds to react. Not all the House Sparrows fled. Some dived into bushes. Soon all were back out in the open and feeding - as though nothing had happened. The recording opens with calls from a Robin at 0:02 and 0:04; then the Robin broadcasts a series of ticking notes at 0:07 until the end of the ninth second. At 0:15 a Blackbird alarms but, just before that, the first wave of House Sparrows erupt into flight at 0:12.  By 0:15 the remainder explode. By the sixteenth second, a total of 80 House Sparrows have left the ground. Those that did not fly away completely (but are still within the bush) start to 'dust themselves down' and are calling. House Sparrows use a 'meep' call when they are agitated. Often it is doubled into a fast repeat that reminds me of the 'meep meep' of the Roadrunner cartoon bird. Especially from 0:18, a chorus of meep notes can be heard.  Although they are not 'doubled up' on this clip, under other circumstances when just one individual becomes uneasy, it frequently cries wolf with a 'meep meep' that serves as a clarion red alert to all that hear it. In fact, not just House Sparrows react to the signal - but  other birds too.
author: Anthony McGeehan

title: XC140293 Lazuli Bunting (Passerina amoena)
secondary_labels: ["Catharus ustulatus_Swainson's Thrush", 'Contopus cooperi_Olive-sided Flycatcher', 'Regulus calendula_Ruby-crowned Kinglet', "Geothlypis tolmiei_MacGillivray's Warbler"]
location: Wright Creek, Prince George, British Columbia
description:
- four songs by same adult male.
- extraneous sounds edited by silencing rather than cutting out to preserve time interval between songs.
- bird singing from mixed forest edge about 5 meters up a Trembling Aspen.
- habitat is grass pastures with fields separated by blocks of mixed conifer (spruce/fir/pine) and deciduous (trembling aspen/cottonwood) forest; forest floor with medium understorey of thimbleberry, saskatoon, and rose; forest edge shrubs and vegetation include willows, rose, saskatoon, common cow-parsnip.
- UTM coordinates from Google Earth: Zone 10U 518349.04 E, 5996841.67 N (WGS84) 
- Lazuli Bunting has been pushing rapidly northward in central BC the past decade and has become established as a breeder in the Prince George area over the past three years. 
- this recording is an attempt to document the main song variant used by these northern vanguard breeders.
- recording device: H2 Zoom.
- sound editing done in Audacity.
- recording available in WAV format upon email request.
background: Swainson's Thrush (Catharus ustulatus); Olive-sided Flycatcher (Contopus cooperi); Ruby-crowned Kinglet (Regulus calendula); MacGillivray's Warbler (Geothlypis tolmiei)
author: Jack Bowling

title: XC195038 Long-tailed Duck (Clangula hyemalis)
location: Braddock Bay, Monroe County, New York
description:
Full 11 minutes of audio: http://macaulaylibrary.org/audio/139678

eBird checklist: http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S4753205 

A huge concentration of Long-tailed Ducks resting on the water, diving for food (apparently Zebra Mussels) and calling like crazy. The flock of 1750 was counted by groups of 25. Numbers of Long-tailed Ducks elsewhere along the shore were down condiserably from past weeks. We wonderered if there were exceptional feeding conditions here in areas that had been covered with ice most of the winter.
author: Jessie H. Barry

More details of the context of this recording may be found here: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S25507224>

This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with a Sennheiser mic and Røde Rec application. This is an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of these birds' utterances.

description:
The recording starts with presumed male flying high over presumed female in nest. It was calling in a flight display carrying what appeared to be a clump of grass.  The grass looks similar to a fish and a Bald Eagle was following closely.

The presumed male then flew and called much closer to nest, follow by a dive at 1:26 towards the nest with female. The male continued to call.  The female finally responded with some calls.  The male called more and then dove (at 3:03) towards and landed on the nest at 3:08.  A least one of them called some more from the nest, with a few more Ospreys calling in background that were attracted to the activities.
author: Paul Marvin

secondary_labels: ["Calypte anna_Anna's Hummingbird", "Thryomanes bewickii_Bewick's Wren", 'Fulica americana_American Coot']
location: San Luis Obispo, San Luis Obispo County, California
description: This Osprey was feeding on a fish 50 feet up in a sycamore above Los Osos Creek, 500 feet away from me. It was calling during a break from eating. It might have been warning off a Red-tailed Hawk in the area. The sky was clear with a few scattered clouds. The first call was at 10:19 AM. I edited out talking, traffic, handling noise, and the long silence between these two calls. The length of time between beginning of first call and beginning of second was 12 min, 15 sec. I also applied light noise reduction and normalized volume. Here, the second call is at 1:59.
background: Anna's Hummingbird (Calypte anna); Bewick's Wren (Thryomanes bewickii); American Coot (Fulica americana)
author: Thomas G. Graves

title: XC139702 Pectoral Sandpiper (Calidris melanotos)
location: Gaswell Road, Barrow, North Slope Borough, Alaska
description: natural vocalization; song and mechanical wing noises from a male bird in a flight display over wet tundra.  During the display the bird flew low (about 0.5m) off the ground in a horizontal flight with it's chest inflated and drooping down while giving the low hooting song and the weird mechanical wing noises, before suddenly undulating three or four times up as high as 3m and then swinging back around to where it started.  After the horizontal portion of the display the rest of the display was completely silent.
author: Andrew Spencer

title: XC139703 Pectoral Sandpiper (Calidris melanotos)
location: Gaswell Road, Barrow, North Slope Borough, Alaska
description: natural vocalization; courtship display from a male bird on the ground pursuing a female.  While displaying the male ran with his tail cocked up, undertail coverts flared, and in a hunched over posture.  At the end of the cut both birds take off, with the male pursuing the female, giving the weird gurgly call.
author: Andrew Spencer

title: XC188559 Pectoral Sandpiper (Calidris melanotos)
location: Ikroavik Lake, Barrow, North Slope Borough, Alaska
description: natural vocalizations; calls from several birds both perched and in flight on somewhat wet tundra that had many drier patches interspersed.  The initial series of bubbly chase calls are from three different males chasing each other, with a female bird giving the loud trill call.  The subsequent raspy calls are from the female bird on the ground, appearing to be performing a distraction display running hunkered down through the grass with its rump exposed and tail flared.  The low pitched gurgle and then hooting song that follow are from one of the previous males in flight, returning from the chase.  The female then does more of her raspy calls before the singing male starts a tail-cocked display while running on the ground after the female and giving the series of lower-pitched raspy calls.  The male bird then breaks into (at 0:40) an alternating series of fast, modulated low-pitched hoots and higher pitched, mechanical sounding, rising/falling trills while the female gives the louder modulated calls.  In short, a remarkable variety of displays and calls all in about a minute!
author: Andrew Spencer

location: Colorado River in vicinity of Picacho, Imperial County, California
description: Calls made near an active eyrie. Presumed male (the adult not incubating) attacked an intruder near the nest (in flight), and the presumed female (adult incubating) flew off the eyrie and flew close to the scuffle. At least the two territorial birds seemed to be calling during the scuffle at the beginning of this recording. I didn't see what happened to the intruder. The presumed male continued to fly around the area while the presumed female returned to the nest (very soft screeching calls at 0:43), then the male flew upriver and directly overhead, calling.

title: XC397713 Pine Grosbeak (Pinicola enucleator)
description: Although I am 9 meters below the birds, they are very quiet in general so I can barely hear them in the recording.  Up in the remote Chuska Mountains in Pine, Spruce, Aspen forest in a section of a canyon where it is a little more closed.  A spring provides a nice seep of water which the birds utilize after foraging.  All female type birds, 9 total individuals seen.
author: Janine McCabe

title: XC404478 Pine Grosbeak (Pinicola enucleator)
description: Flock of 6 Pine Grosbeak calling while feeding on Douglas-fir (Pseudotsuga menziesii) cones. One female-type bird (mostly gray with no obvious red) was singing from the top of a Douglas-fir. None of the calls or song were particularly loud, and although I was directly beneath the birds, standing in deep snow, the recordings are faint. This recording was amplified to audibly bring out the songs and calls. These are visible and unclipped on the original WAV recording. Some of this recording is potentially female song or sub-song. Recorded with an Olympus LS-10 linear PCM microphone.
author: Walter Szeliga

location: Big Bay State Park, Ashland, Wisconsin
description:
Two segments from a pair of birds.  It's unclear whether the calls were from the male or the female or both.  In the first segment, there were several calls in flight before landing about 20m from where I stood along the shore of the lagoon. After landing, they swam slowly toward me and watched me from a distance of 5-10m for about 15 minutes.  The second segment is the same pair calling as they flushed from the water and flew away.

Recorded with internal microphones of Olympus LS-10S.
background: Common Loon (Gavia immer); Alder Flycatcher (Empidonax alnorum); Common Yellowthroat (Geothlypis trichas); American Crow (Corvus brachyrhynchos); Song Sparrow (Melospiza melodia)

These birds were all feeding near the top of tall, seeding hemlocks in tall second-growth mixed conifer forest.

title: XC110188 Red Crossbill (Loxia curvirostra)
description: natural vocalization; 'chitoo' calls from a streaky juvenile 'type 2' bird perched near the top of a seeding larch tree, in mixed ponderosa pine and larch woodland.  This bird was mostly sitting still giving these calls as an adult moved around nearby but never fed it.
author: Andrew Spencer

title: XC113900 Red Crossbill (Loxia curvirostra)
description:
Flock abot 26 birds; composing 3 types of call - 2 not reported by work of Magnus S Robb - 
most of birds has similar calls for western dark Siberian taiga some similar to reported from eastern dark Siberian taiga and:

- call like in   0:00.715 is not reported by Magnus S. Robb. but has some similarities also in excitement call to type "F" (I have named it "Western Scotch Pine cohort")  - So I have named it as "Fe" with name - "Eastern Scotch Pine cohort" (named in XC sometimes as x) - this birds are also very similar to "Siberian Pine cohort" or it is the same wandering throughout continent depending on "fertile years" of Norway and Siberian Spruce 

- call like in   0:03.257 is similar to reported C type call but with usual for continental spruce cohort spearheaded and bent right arm - more prominent like in "Cd" type soo I mark it as "Cf" call and named "Northern Spruce cohort" - placed east of "Scandinavian Spruce cohort" this birds are very similar to "Siberian Spruce cohort"  or it is the same wandering throughout continent depending on "fertile years" of Scotch and Siberian Pine

- cal on 0:00.643     0:03.883 is similar to "D" type reported in work of Magnus S Robb  and can belogns to unknown  Siberian Larch cohort

And excitement calls throughout the recording

Birds was feeding on Picea pungens with small cones similar to eastern Syberian Spruve - Picea obovata, rather omitting native Norway Spruce - Picea alba what can suggesting the origin of the bird flock rather form East Siberian cohorts
author: Jarek Matusiak

title: XC113901 Red Crossbill (Loxia curvirostra)
description:
song or subsong, highly cleaned; becouse of sound in 0:30.0 sounds like singing bird most limilar to XC106703 recorded in Bolshoy Kundysh in Russian Federation, by Albert Lastukhin,

Singing bird belong to named "fe" type - not reported by Magnus S. Robb. but has some similarities also in excitement call to type "F" (I have named it "Western Scotch Pine cohort") - So I have named it as "Fe" with name - "Eastern Scotch Pine cohort" (named in XC sometimes as x - but prefer "fe" along the Magnus and beter finding results on WWW) - this birds are also very similar to "Siberian Pine cohort" or it is the same wandering throughout continent depending on "fertile years" of Norway and Siberian Spruce
author: Jarek Matusiak

title: XC113904 Red Crossbill (Loxia curvirostra)
description: sound of feeding on spruce cones flock scared by Sparrowhawk and after the while taking of; sounds more similarly to XC106703 recorded in Bolshoy Kundysh in Russian Federation, by Albert Lastukhin
author: Jarek Matusiak

title: XC114345 Red Crossbill (Loxia curvirostra)

title: XC123615 Red Crossbill (Loxia curvirostra)
description:
I decide to separate recording of breeding birds from Carpathian Mountains in separate "Carpathian Spruce cohort" of birds  with code "G" I prefer to name them as "cohorts" instead of "types". In the work of Magnus S Robb the birds has similar right arm with important marked "step" of sound as have e and d from B type reported mostly from around the Mediterranean Sea including L.c. poliogyna on the West but not Eastern L.c. guillemardi. 
From the same cohort is recording of bird: XC141520
author: Jarek Matusiak

title: XC123616 Red Crossbill (Loxia curvirostra)
location: Národný park Slovenský Kras (near  Plešivec), Rožňava, Košice Region
description:
Call not reported by Magnus S. Robb. but has some similarities also in excitement call to type "F" (I have named it "Western Scotch Pine cohort")  - So I have named it as "Fe" with name - "Eastern Scotch Pine cohort" (named in XC sometimes as x) - this birds are also very similar to "Siberian Pine cohort" or it is the same wandering throughout continent depending on "fertile years" of Norway and Siberian Spruce.

Sounds strikingly different from breeding in region birds from "g" type "Carpathian Spruce cohort" e.g.: XC123617 ; XC123615 ; XC141520

Sounds more similarly to XC106703 recorded in Bolshoy Kundysh in Russian Federation, by Albert Lastukhin
author: Jarek Matusiak

location: Montana de Oro State Park, Los Osos, San Luis Obispo County, California
description:
Going out on a limb with this ID: I recorded one later this day, the notes are a bit slower and more slurred than the Black-headed Grosbeak, and no Black-headed Grosbeaks were seen by me on this day. 
This individual is likely the same as the one in the background of XC480054 , as the sequence of notes is the same, although this one is slightly faster. 
Bird singing in riparian habitat. 
(Recorded with Marantz PMD 661, Sennheiser ME62, 24 inch Roché parabola)
background: Wilson's Warbler (Cardellina pusilla); Spotted Towhee (Pipilo maculatus); California Scrub Jay (Aphelocoma californica); Wrentit (Chamaea fasciata); Swainson's Thrush (Catharus ustulatus)

title: XC368057 Rock Wren (Salpinctes obsoletus)
description:
Edited: Using Raven Lite, I filtered out background noise (airplanes & highway) from above and below the Rock Wren call.

Habitat: lava fields, collapsed lava tubes, green rabbitbrush, wyoming sagebrush and utah juniper were the dominant shrub species. Forbs known included lomatium and primrose. 

Behavior: Actively foraging around a collapsed lava tube, darting in and out of broken lava rocks while calling. Occasionally took breaks to sing atop utah juniper, rocky outcrops, and dead snags. 

Plumage: Distant views, pale buffy front, deep knee-bends.

Sex: Unknown

Weather: Overcast and cool, very light precipitation for about 3 minutes.
background: American Robin (Turdus migratorius); Horned Lark (Eremophila alpestris)
author: Jeremy Welch

title: XC132947 Rufous Hummingbird (Selasphorus rufus)
location: Old Mission Dam, San Diego River, San Diego County
description: Messy recording, with two displays at the start and 0:07, regular wing buzz later before a few calls at the end; this is from a migrant adult male over chaparral slopes, behavior not usually noted by me in migration in this area, but several times in the cool, wet spring of this year (another recording from 20 April of this year); recording originally put on Xeno-Canto as Calliope, identification questioned in a forum by Nathan Pieplow; beyond the objective basis for his re-identification, I went to my field notes, which were specific about displaying Rufous and said nothing about displaying Calliope (the species was present, not displaying); not quite sure how I went wrong, but wrong I went; thank you, Nathan;
background: Bewick's Wren (Thryomanes bewickii); Northern Raven (Corvus corax)

description: 2 birds chasing away a Northern Harrier (which can be heard at 0:55 and throughout the rest of the recording). After they forced the Harrier to land on a small brush and dive bombed it a bit they turned their attention to a Rough Legged Hawk that was flying over and they chased that  away. There's a nice mix of vocalizations in this recording as well as some wing claps. Habitat a swampy field with a brushy edge, at least 10 other Short-Eared's were present at this time.
author: Bruce Lagerquist

title: XC205575 Snow Bunting (Plectrophenax nivalis)
location: Forest Road 152 area, off of Gunflint Trail, Superior National Forest (near Grand Marais), Cook County, Minnesota
description: I was searching for Snow Buntings at a large open gravel covered area where I saw a number of them several days before. At first I couldn't find any, but then one found me: it was very close and it was walking my way. I followed it closely, taking pictures. It then spotted another Snow Bunting (better company than me) flying overhead, so it flew up to greet it while calling. They both returned near me while contining to call. I quickly grabbed my microphone and recorded most of the action.
author: Paul Marvin

title: XC167610 Snow Goose (Anser caerulescens)
location: Ave. B and 50th West, Lancaster, Los Angeles County, California
description:
Natural vocalizations by a flight of about 190 snow geese.  There were also 8 Ross' geese mixed in although I don't know if the latter species was also vocalizing.

Location: agricultural fields surrounded by desert sage scrub.  The geese had been feeding on a field before they flew right over us.

An airplane is also audible.

Equipment: Olympus LS-10S equipped with a Sennheiser MKE-400 short shotgun microphone.

Modifications to the file: cropped at both ends.
author: Lance A. M. Benner

title: XC357958 Snow Goose (Anser caerulescens)
location: Sonny Bono Salton Sea National Wildlife Refuge, near Calipatria, Imperial County, California
description:
I was waiting for this moment since first seeing the large flocks of Snow Geese on this trip. I’d see them on land or in the water, occasionally taking off in flight. I was hoping a flock would fly directly over, allowing me to aim straight up to record, and they did this for me in this recording. Stereo would have been nice, but my stereo mics are omnidirectional and would have captured too much background noise. This recording was with one omni-mic and my 24 inch dish. 
    And I wish I had been able to video this spectacle: I expected an unorganized mob of geese, but they had not only arranged in their “V” formations already, but in multiple groups going in different directions at different heights above me. This created a spectacular geometric effect of moving quadrilaterals of blue sky boarderd by lines of white geese.
background: Gadwall (Mareca strepera); Song Sparrow (Melospiza melodia); Marsh Wren (Cistothorus palustris)
author: Thomas G. Graves

Recorded as I waded through deep, thickly vegetated, beach-marshland waters, trying in vain to find a fordable point to reach the other side of the marsh. Bird was approximately 8m from me. Didn't seem bothered at all by my presence, even though I couldn't see it most of the time, as it was calling off and on as it moved around in the marsh in front of me, and eventually fluttered right past me to a new spot, where it started calling again. It had sung a while before, but I wasn't anywhere near close enough to get a good recording of it at the time. Weather: cool (50 degrees F), cloudy, calm. Slight amplification, high pass filter applied to reduce noise.
background: Barn Swallow (Hirundo rustica)
author: Rachel Hudson

title: XC148241 Swainson's Thrush (Catharus ustulatus)
description:
IAvH-CSA 11167

Aunque el audio dice _Mionectes oleagineus_, la identidad fue discutida y corregida en xeno-canto por Tayler Brooks, confirmada por Oscar Humberto Marín-Gomez y Andrés Angulo. El mensaje original fue:

Hi there,

I'm not hearing Mionectes in this recording, but the short upslurring whistles sound like a good match for Swainson's Thrush. Compare with XC259189.

Cheers,

~Tayler

Identidad corregida también en la Colección de Sonidos Ambientales (Orlando Acevedo Charry: 2018-09-24)

title: XC316431 Swainson's Thrush (Catharus ustulatus)
description:
Natural sound. Birds perched 1-2m above the ground in a privet thicket along the edge of the grounds just behind a mulberry tree with ripe berries. One bird singing initially, but sounded as though a second joined in at times. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 2 kHz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
author: J.R. Rigby

title: XC396845 Tundra Swan (Cygnus columbianus)
secondary_labels: ['Grus grus_Common Crane', 'Anthus pratensis_Meadow Pipit', 'Anthus spinoletta_Water Pipit']
description:
A flock of purely Tundra swans coming in to their roost during the evening twilight. All members of the flock were visually identified. I followed the flock with a parabolic microphone as they flew by, over a landscape probably also used by whooper swans for roosting. Birds on the ground were hidden, so there might also be calls from whooper swans on the ground in the recording. At the end it can be heard how the tundra swans land on a water surface (the woosh of the water can be heard) on the other end of the area (invisible to the observer) and start social interactions.
The area is a turf mining complex beeing partly rewetted and renatured. The swans, bean geese and cranes use the water surfaces in the renaturing areas for roosting.
background: Common Crane (Grus grus); Meadow Pipit (Anthus pratensis); Water Pipit (Anthus spinoletta)
author: Raoul Kima

title: XC255604 Violet-green Swallow (Tachycineta thalassina)
description:
This 1+ minute recording documents a flock of swallows swarming me. The primary vocalist was an adult female Violet-green Swallow. Also present was an adult male Violet-green Swallow and an adult Barn Swallow (sex not determined). Other swallows were present but were not focused on but I assume they were probably their youngsters. The female was protecting a juvenile Barn Swallow (which she fed) perched on the nest box that she had raised her young in. This juvenile was incapable of sustained flight and just was resting near the VGSW box. These parents were attempting to drive me away. The recording begins with a volley of notes from the female and she each time she approaches me throughout the recording she is stooping on me. She also spends some time just circling me and giving single more spaced calls. At 0:17 the male make a two phrase scratchy vocalization at the bottom of a dive directed at me. At 0:44 a Barn Swallow begins to make noise. At 0:48 a Barn Sallow begins to chase an adult Common Raven.

The Birds of North America account says this about the alarm call: “Alarm” call. No published description, but apparent alarm calls recorded by D. J. Borror in El Paso Co., CO, are shown in Fig. 3 . Also a “zwrack” call, similar to that of Purple Martin (Progne subis), used in high-intensity alarm situations (Brown 1983).

Additional details regarding context may be found at: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S24178105>

This recording was made with an iPhone 4s with Sennheiser microphone and Røde Rec application.
background: Barn Swallow (Hirundo rustica)
author: Elias Aristides Elias

location: Watts Flats WMA, Town of Harmony (near  Ashville), Chautauqua County, New York
type: Winnowing Sound. Made by wind rushing through outspread tail feathers during cou
description: From Cornell Lab of Ornithology: "All About Birds." The sound is usually produced as the birds dive, but can also be generated when the bird levels out following a dive. Males perform the winnowing flight to defend territory and attract mates. Females also winnow prior to breeding, but stop as soon as they begin to nest.

title: XC377125 Wild Turkey (Meleagris gallopavo)

location: California (near  Santa Margarita), San Luis Obispo County, California
description:
A female Wild Turkey and about 6 chicks were walking down the road when hawk flew in over them and perched in an oak tree. You can here the clucking calls and their foot falls on the road. I’m assuming the hawk was an immature Red-tailed as I recorded a family of Red-tailed Hawks calling back and forth over the oak savanna just after this in the same area.
     There is also a barking sound I believe is the female Wild Turkey: 0:20 , 0:30 , 0:34 .
     Any ideas?
background: Wild Turkey (Meleagris gallopavo); Eurasian Collared Dove (Streptopelia decaocto); Chestnut-backed Chickadee (Poecile rufescens); Ash-throated Flycatcher (Myiarchus cinerascens); Red-tailed Hawk (Buteo jamaicensis)
